Mini SOC Lab – Wazuh SIEM Detection Report
## 1. Introduction

This project demonstrates the creation of a small Security Operations Center (SOC) laboratory environment using Wazuh SIEM, Sysmon, and Windows security logging.

The objective of this lab is to simulate common attacker techniques and develop custom detection rules to identify suspicious activity.

The lab includes:

-A Wazuh SIEM server responsible for log ingestion and detection

-A Windows 10 endpoint acting as the victim machine

-A Kali Linux system used to simulate attacker activity

The environment allows testing detection scenarios such as:

-Brute force authentication attempts

-Suspicious PowerShell execution

-Network port scanning

## 2. Lab Architecture

The laboratory environment consists of three virtual machines connected through a host-only network.

Machine	Role	IP Address
Wazuh Server	SIEM / Log analysis	192.168.56.101
Windows 10	Victim endpoint	192.168.56.102
Kali Linux	Attacker machine	192.168.56.103

Logs generated on the Windows endpoint are collected by the Wazuh agent and forwarded to the Wazuh manager, where they are processed and correlated using detection rules.

## 3. Telemetry Configuration

To ensure sufficient visibility, several logging mechanisms were enabled on the Windows endpoint.

Windows Security Logging

Windows audit policies were configured to log authentication events, including:

-successful logons

-failed logon attempts

-These events are essential for detecting brute force attacks.

Example event ID monitored:

-4625 – Failed logon attempt
-PowerShell Logging

PowerShell Script Block Logging was enabled to capture executed PowerShell commands.

This allows the detection of suspicious commands such as:

-encoded commands

-remote script execution

-malicious automation

Sysmon Deployment

Sysmon was installed on the Windows endpoint to provide detailed system telemetry including:

-process creation

-network connections

-file modifications

-registry changes

Important Sysmon event IDs used in this project include:

Event ID	Description
1	Process creation
3	Network connection
11	File creation

## 4. Wazuh Agent Deployment

A Wazuh agent was installed on the Windows endpoint to collect system logs and forward them to the Wazuh server.

The agent successfully connected to the Wazuh manager and began sending telemetry data.

This allowed the SIEM to ingest logs from:

-Windows Event Logs

-Sysmon logs

-PowerShell logging

## 5. Detection Engineering

Three detection rules were implemented to identify suspicious activity in the environment.

Detection 1 – Brute Force Attack
Attack Simulation

-Multiple failed login attempts were generated on the Windows endpoint.

The Windows security event:

-Event ID 4625

indicates a failed authentication attempt.

Detection Logic

A custom Wazuh rule was created to detect multiple failed logon attempts from the same IP within a short time window.

Detection logic:

-5 failed logon attempts
-Within 60 seconds
-From the same IP address

This behaviour is commonly associated with brute force attacks.

Detection 2 – Suspicious PowerShell Execution
Attack Simulation

A PowerShell command using encoded parameters was executed:

powershell.exe -EncodedCommand

Encoded PowerShell commands are frequently used by attackers to hide malicious activity.

Detection Logic

A custom detection rule was created to identify:

-encoded PowerShell commands

-suspicious script execution patterns

This rule uses Sysmon process creation events.

Detection 3 – Port Scanning
Attack Simulation

The Kali Linux machine executed an Nmap scan against the Windows endpoint:

nmap -sS -p- 192.168.56.102

This generates multiple connection attempts to different ports.

Detection Logic

Sysmon network connection events were monitored to detect:

-multiple connection attempts

-from the same source IP

-within a short time window

This behaviour is consistent with reconnaissance activity.

## 6. Threat Hunting

The Wazuh dashboard allows analysts to perform threat hunting queries using ingested logs.

Example queries used in this project include:

agent.name: Victim01

and

data.win.system.eventID:1

These queries help analysts identify suspicious system activity.

## 7. Conclusion

This project demonstrates how a small SOC environment can be built using open-source security tools.

The lab shows how telemetry from Windows systems can be collected, analysed, and correlated to detect malicious behaviour.

Key skills demonstrated include:

-SIEM deployment and configuration

-endpoint telemetry collection

-detection rule creation

-attack simulation

-threat hunting using SIEM tools

This type of environment provides a valuable platform for learning blue team and SOC analyst techniques.

